  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are statutes that address money laundering in many jurisdictions around the world. In the United States, for example, money laundering is primarily addressed by the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970** and the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**. These laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising the origins of illegally obtained funds.\n\n### Key U.S. Statutes:\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**:\n   - Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions (e.g., cash transactions over $10,000) and maintain records to help detect and prevent money laundering.\n   - Established requirements for anti-money laundering (AML) programs.\n\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)**:\n   - Made money laundering a federal crime.\n   - Prohibits knowingly engaging in financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities.\n\n3. **USA PATRIOT Act (2001)**:\n   - Expanded AML requirements, including enhanced due diligence for foreign accounts and stricter penalties for violations.\n   - Strengthened the BSA by increasing oversight and reporting requirements.\n\n### International Efforts:\nGlobally, money laundering is addressed through treaties and organizations such as:\n- **The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**: Sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorism financing.\n- **United Nations Conventions**: For example, the UN Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988) and the UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime (2000) include provisions against money laundering.\n\n### Penalties:\nMoney laundering offenses can result in severe penalties, including:\n- Fines (which can be substantial, often in the millions of dollars).\n- Imprisonment (up to 20 years or more, depending on the jurisdiction and severity of the offense).\n- Asset forfeiture (confiscation of proceeds from illegal activities).\n\nIf you're looking for specifics in a particular jurisdiction or need more detailed information, let me know!",
